Public Bus Trip Observations: Comfort, Crowding, and Behavior

Lindi Zhang

Comfort under Different Bus Crowding Levels

This plot shows how comfort ratings vary depending on how crowded the bus is.

We can observe that the comfort level tends to decrease as the bus becomes more full.

Boxplot of comfort by bus occupancy level. Comfort is lowest when the bus is full.

Headphone Use among Passengers

This bar chart shows how many people were wearing headphones.

Most passengers were wearing headphones sometimes, with fewer wearing them all the time or not at all.

Bar chart of headphone usage groups. “Some” is the most common category.

Comfort Ratings by Time of Day

This chart shows the average comfort score at different times of the day.

It reveals a pattern where comfort may depend on time, may be due to congestion, or may depend on the morning rush hour, evening rush hour, etc.

Bar chart of average comfort per hour. Comfort varies across the day.

Eating Behavior by Hour of Day

This visualization shows how often eating behavior was observed on the bus at different times of the day.

To create this, I extracted the hour from the time_stamp using mutate(hour = hour(...)), then summarized the data using count(hour, eat_or_not). I used facet_wrap("eat_or_not") to split the plot into two separate graph: one for observations which eating was seen (Yes) and another which eating was not (No).

This plot helps to compare the timing of eating behavior versus non-eating behavior during bus trips. We can see that eating was more likely to be observed around midday and early evening hours, while “No” observations were more common in the morning.

Create “small multiples” (multiple small images) to show the eating behavior (yes/no) for each hour of the day. Eating usually takes place at noon and in the evening.
